  "slug": "bigos",
  "title": "Bigos",
  "subtitle": "Polish hunter's stew of sauerkraut, cabbage, and three meats.",
  "excerpt": "Sauerkraut and fresh cabbage stewed slowly with pork shoulder, smoked sausage, beef, onion, dried mushrooms, and prune. The traditional Polish winter pot, made over two days, eaten over the next week.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Bigos is the Polish national stew documented from the medieval Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth through Adam Mickiewicz's Pan Tadeusz (1834, public domain) and into modern Polish farmhouse cookery.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Bigos is a long pot. The first cook takes four hours; you eat it on day two, when it has tasted of itself overnight. The same pot then comes back to the table on day three, four, and five, each reheat adding to the depth. Polish hunters carried bigos into the forest in clay pots; the dish was as much a way of preserving meat through a long cold week as a meal.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Three things matter most. Use a mix of sauerkraut and fresh cabbage, roughly half and half. Use more than one kind of meat, pork shoulder, smoked sausage, and a piece of beef or game work classically. And cook it slowly enough that you can leave it alone for an hour at a time without burning at the bottom of the pan.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
