      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "A 6 to 8 litre lidded Dutch oven. The pot needs to be wider than tall so the moisture has room to evaporate during the long cook.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Render the bacon and brown the meats",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Cook {{streaky-bacon}} of lardons in the Dutch oven over medium heat for 8 minutes until the fat runs and the bacon is crisp. Lift out into a bowl with a slotted spoon. Brown {{pork-shoulder}} of pork shoulder in batches in the rendered fat, 3 minutes a side, until deeply coloured. Lift out to the bowl. Brown {{beef-chuck}} of beef in the same way. Set aside. Brown {{chorizo}} of sausage rounds, 1 minute a side, then lift out.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Build the base",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Tip {{onion}} of sliced onions into the pot. Cook 10 minutes until soft and golden. Stir in {{garlic}} of garlic, {{caraway-seeds}} of caraway, {{juniper-berries}} of juniper, {{bay-leaves}} of bay, and {{allspice}} of allspice for 1 minute. Stir in {{tomato-puree}} of tomato purée and cook 2 minutes.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Combine everything",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Return all the browned meats to the pot. Tip in the shredded fresh cabbage and the drained sauerkraut. Drain the soaked porcini, chop roughly, and add along with their soaking liquid (strain through a sieve first to leave any grit behind). Add {{prunes}} of prunes. Pour in {{red-wine}} of red wine and {{stock-beef}} of beef stock. Stir in {{honey}} of honey and {{black-pepper}} of black pepper. Don't add salt yet; the sauerkraut and bacon both add salt.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Slow cook",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Bring to a gentle simmer. Cover, drop the heat to its lowest setting, and cook for 3 hours, stirring every 30 minutes. The pot should barely bubble. Uncover and cook for another hour to reduce the liquid and concentrate the flavours. Taste and add salt only if needed. Let cool, then refrigerate overnight.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Reheat to serve",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "On day two, lift any fat from the surface (or stir it in for a richer dish). Bring the pot back to a gentle simmer over medium heat, then drop low and cook for 45 minutes. Taste once more for salt and pepper. Serve in deep bowls with dark rye bread and a glass of cold vodka or a bracing dry red.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Troubleshooting",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "intro": null,
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Rinse the sauerkraut lightly before adding, especially if the brand is very sharp. The honey and prunes balance the sour; if still too acid, add another tablespoon of honey.",
              "cause": "Strong sauerkraut, or no balancing sweet element.",
              "symptom": "Bigos too sour"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Bigos needs the lowest possible simmer for 3 to 4 hours. A boiling pot toughens the meat; the right heat is barely a bubble.",
              "cause": "Cooked too fast.",
              "symptom": "Meat tough at the bite"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Use a heat-diffuser plate if your hob runs hot. Stir every 30 minutes; add 100 ml of stock or water if the bottom looks dry.",
              "cause": "Heat too high, or not enough liquid.",
              "symptom": "Burnt at the bottom of the pan"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Drain the sauerkraut in a sieve for 5 minutes before adding. Bagged sauerkraut from the supermarket carries a lot of brine; the jarred Polish-deli version is firmer.",
              "cause": "Sauerkraut not drained before adding.",
              "symptom": "Sauerkraut limp and watery"
            }
          ],
          "heading": "Common problems"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Bigos is the dish of Polish hunting parties, of Christmas Eve in Lithuanian-Polish households, of long winter Sundays in Kraków. Adam Mickiewicz devoted a passage of Pan Tadeusz to its making. Eat with thick dark rye bread, a small cold glass of vodka, and good appetite, bigos is not subtle.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
